2 HOUSE BILL 297
1 Article – Labor and Employment
2 Section 11–808.1 and 11–810
3 Annotated Code of Maryland
4 (2025 Replacement Volume)
5 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
6 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
7 Article – Labor and Employment
8 11–808.
9 (a) An individual may obtain a high school diploma by examination as provided
10 in this section if the individual:
11 (1) has not obtained a high school diploma;
12 (2) resides in this State; and
13 (3) except as provided in subsection (b) of this section:
14 (i) is not subject to compulsory school attendance under § 7–301 of
15 the Education Article; and
16 (ii) has withdrawn from a regular full–time public or private school
17 program.
18 (b) An individual is not subject to the requirements of subsection (a)(3) of this
19 section if the individual participates in:
20 (1) a GED Option Program administered by the State Department of
21 Education that creates a pathway to a high school diploma by examination for currently
22 enrolled high school English language learner students under the age of 21 years who have
23 experienced interrupted education and have a lower level of English proficiency than their
24 peers; OR
25 (2) THE GED OPTION PILOT PROGRAM ESTABLISHED UNDER §
26 11–808.1 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
27 11–808.1.
28 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “PILOT PROGRAM” MEANS THE GED OPTION PILOT
29 PROGRAM.
30 (B) (1) THERE IS A GED OPTION PILOT PROGRAM IN THE STATE.

HOUSE BILL 297 3
1 (2) THE PURPOSE OF THE PILOT PROGRAM IS TO EXPAND THE GED
2 OPTION PROGRAM TO STUDENTS BEYOND ENGLISH LANGUAGE LEARNERS IN
3 SELECTED SCHOOL DISTRICTS TO ENSURE THAT THE STUDENTS HAVE A PATHWAY
4 TO OBTAIN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA AND ARE PREPARED TO ENTER
5 POSTSECONDARY PROGRAMMING OR THE WORKFORCE.
6 (C) THE PILOT PROGRAM SHALL BEGIN IN THE 2027–2028 SCHOOL YEAR
7 AND SHALL CONTINUE FOR 2 SCHOOL YEARS.
8 (D) THE DEPARTMENT:
9 (1) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
10 EDUCATION AND THE PUBLIC SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENTS’ ASSOCIATION OF
11 MARYLAND, SHALL DEVELOP CRITERIA, INCLUDING RECOGNITION OF GEOGRAPHIC
12 DIVERSITY, FOR THE SELECTION OF AT LEAST THREE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS TO
13 PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT PROGRAM; AND
14 (2) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
15 EDUCATION, SHALL USE THE CRITERIA DEVELOPED UNDER ITEM (1) OF THIS
16 SUBSECTION TO SELECT AT LEAST THREE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS TO PARTICIPATE
17 IN THE PILOT PROGRAM.
18 (E) EACH COUNTY SUPERINTENDENT FROM A PARTICIPATING LOCAL
19 SCHOOL SYSTEM MAY SELECT UP TO 150 STUDENTS TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT
20 PROGRAM.
21 (F) A STUDENT SELECTED TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT PROGRAM:
22 (1) MAY BEGIN THE GED OPTION PROGRAM WHEN THE STUDENT IS
23 AT LEAST 17 YEARS OLD;
24 (2) MUST BE AT SIGNIFICANT RISK OF NOT SUCCESSFULLY
25 COMPLETING HIGH SCHOOL; AND
26 (3) SHALL TAKE THE HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA BY EXAMINATION
27 BEFORE THE CONCLUSION OF THE GED OPTION PROGRAM.
28 (G) THE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION
29 SHALL EXPLORE OPTIONS FOR EXPANDING THE GED OPTION PROGRAM BASED ON
30 RESULTS OF THE PILOT PROGRAM.
31 (H) (1) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1, 2028, AND DECEMBER 1, 2029, THE
32 DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION JOINTLY SHALL

4 HOUSE BILL 297
1 REPORT TO THE GOVERNOR AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
2 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY REGARDING THE
3 EFFECTIVENESS OF THE PILOT PROGRAM.
4 (2) THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
5 SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE:
6 (I) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS PARTICIPATING IN THE PILOT
7 PROGRAM FROM EACH PARTICIPATING LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM;
8 (II) FEEDBACK FROM EDUCATORS, STUDENTS, AND PARENTS OF
9 STUDENTS PARTICIPATING IN THE PILOT PROGRAM ON WAYS TO IMPROVE THE
10 GED OPTION PROGRAM;
11 (III) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS WHO EARNED A HIGH SCHOOL
12 DIPLOMA AS A RESULT OF COMPLETING THE PILOT PROGRAM; AND
13 (IV) AN EVALUATION OF THE PILOT PROGRAM AND THE GED
14 OPTION PROGRAM WITH ANY RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVEMENTS.
15 (I) THE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION
16 JOINTLY MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS TO IMPLEMENT THE PILOT PROGRAM.
17 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
18 as follows:
19 Article – Labor and Employment
20 11–810.
21 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY” MEANS AN
22 ALTERNATIVE PATHWAY TO EARN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA IN THE STATE.
23 (B) THE MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IS A METHOD TO RECOGNIZE AND
24 CERTIFY HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA ACHIEVEMENT THROUGH DEMONSTRATED
25 ACADEMIC AND CAREER COMPETENCIES, INCLUDING WORKFORCE EXPERIENCE.
26 (C) AN INDIVIDUAL MAY OBTAIN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA THROUGH THE
27 MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IF THE INDIVIDUAL:
28 (1) HAS NOT OBTAINED A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA;
29 (2) RESIDES IN THE STATE;

HOUSE BILL 297 5
1 (3) IS NOT SUBJECT TO THE COMPULSORY SCHOOL ATTENDANCE
2 REQUIREMENT UNDER § 7–301 OF THE EDUCATION ARTICLE; AND
3 (4) HAS WITHDRAWN FROM A REGULAR FULL–TIME PUBLIC OR
4 PRIVATE SCHOOL PROGRAM.
5 (D) TO EARN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA THROUGH THE MDIPLOMAWORKS
6 PATHWAY, AN INDIVIDUAL SHALL DEMONSTRATE EQUIVALENCY TO A MARYLAND
7 HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA BY COMPLETION OF A COMBINATION OF THE FOLLOWING
8 COMPONENTS AS APPROVED BY THE DEPARTMENT:
9 (1) EARNING INDUSTRY–RECOGNIZED CREDENTIALS;
10 (2) DEMONSTRATING FOUNDATIONAL ACADEMIC SKILLS THROUGH
11 FORMAL ASSESSMENTS;
12 (3) COMPLETING CAREER AND TECHNICAL EDUCATION
13 COURSEWORK; AND
14 (4) COMPLETING AN ON–THE–JOB LEARNING EXPERIENCE.
15 (E) A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA SHALL BE AWARDED TO AN INDIVIDUAL WHO
16 COMPLETES THE MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
17 REGULATIONS ADOPTED BY THE SECRETARY AND THE STATE BOARD OF
18 EDUCATION.
19 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Maryland Department of
20 Labor shall publish on its website, and include in any publications that describe how adults
21 may obtain a high school diploma, information on the MDiplomaWorks pathway
22 established under § 11–810 of the Labor and Employment Article, as enacted by Section 1
23 of this Act, in order to inform potentially eligible applicants about the new pathway to
24 obtain a high school diploma.
25 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
26 October 1, 2026. Section 1 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 4 years and, at
27 the end of September 30, 2030, Section 1 of this Act, with no further action required by the
28 General Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.

